<div style="text-align:center; font-size:64px; color:#2a0134; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5.5px #6e4a75, 1px 4.5px 10px #c9a8ce, 1px 4.5px 10px #c9a8ce; font-family:Mozilla Headline;">"Where Every Block Carries Hate"</div></div>

{{User:Liminalityyyyy/Template:ClassicImageBox|file=Allthesameperson.jpg|text=You were never the priority.|width=440px}}

<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>

<div class="mainbox">
Repetitiveness.

You see the same high rise apartments on a repeating grid of wide avenues for eternity.

Lifelessness.

There are no plants to be seen nor parks to help you breathe.

Emptiness.

Within the constructs there are no furnishings nor paint. Just concrete walls, indefinitely under construction.<br><br>

Those were the highlights of your ventures throughout the city. You have been seeing the same sights for what you can tell is... a long time. After all this exploring, you finally decide to lay down on the benches in one of the scarce parks.

It compels you.

The air is cold, the bench grants no cushion, and you're exposed to all the elements and noise. Despite all of that, you somehow swiftly fall into slumber.

----

{{User:Liminalityyyyy/Template:ClassicImageBox|file=Speedrunts.jpg|text= |width=440px}}

You're awoken by the immediate discomfort on your head, lower back, and thighs as they rest on thin metal bars elevated above a bench. Your feet are wedged below one of the bars, bending your ankles as it conforms itself to the tiny space betwixt the bench and metal bars. You immediately knew that the bench you fell asleep on wasn't the same as the bench you woke up in.

After that realization, you attempt to take a note of your surroundings. Instead of seeing blocks upon blocks of lifeless concrete buildings along with wide empty avenues, you see buildings of various architectural styles all around, dotted by modern skyscrapers, on a network of thin roads. The buildings you see are not exactly endearing, yet their presentation confers them an ounce of soul at the very least, in contrast to the inhuman constructs in the last place.

You wedge your feet out of their predicament. They're still painful and mildly disfigured from being wedged under the metal bar for a... long time, and you figure that for the time being, merely standing up will be agonizing. As you move your body, even making slight movements, it pains and aches from lying in such an unorthodox position, especially your lower back. You think of falling onto the pavement below, though the fall might intensify your already wrenching pains. Is it not bizarre how it is preferable to lay down on the cold, hard concrete pavement than something whose whole purpose is to provide rest and comfort? No, for the benches have been subverted to a weapon of perhaps even interdiction.

But that is just the tip of the iceberg. Eventually, after a few minutes, your aches mellow out, and you somewhat comfortably move your body into a sitting position. There are still some pains, but they're relatively tolerable. You wait a few minutes more, pondering the thought that the entire dilemma earlier would have been avoided merely from the lack of those metal bars. Your surroundings may be a tad endearing and the air a tad fresher, but you're still in this perdition, where one may never find any true rest nor escape. The bars, and other obstacles yet more to come are a reminder of the wicked nature of this Sheol.

{{User:Liminalityyyyy/Template:ClassicImageBox|file=Reallyitsthatexpensive.jpg|text= |width=440px}}

Your body eventually regains itself, then you muster the strength to stand up and walk around, to fully take in your surroundings. You notice that the bench you woke up on isn't the only one of it's class. There are more benches all around your space with metal bars. There are some benches with slight slopes, one that resemble chairs more than benches. The space you are in right now may visually resemble a park, a brief respite from the chaos of life as it would back home, yet it is anything but. Even just seating isn't viable on some of the 'benches' that you've seen that 'adorn' this 'park'.

Crossing the road you examine the buildings on the other side. Spikes lay the ground and windowsills where one would find shelter from the rain or sun. They are not harmful yet they are unpleasant. Some surfaces even sport boulders. You figure that if you were to find any form of respite within this place, you would have to enter the buildings, but alas, there are no doors and all windows are tinted dark, and you lack the energy to attempt a break-in, as if that's even possible with these. However, you encounter a cafe immediately by taking a left turn. The windows aren't tinted and there's an open door. It's got everything a cafe has to offer, even some food to keep you going, and its coziness permeates the air, yet there's no seating. Just an empty concrete floor. But at least you can munch on the snacks while on the go, yet they are just snacks, they will never truly fulfill you.

You stay in the cafe for a while, notwithstanding its lack of hallmark amenities. The cafe will eventually run dry the longer you stay and the more you ingest, so it is high time that you vacate. Maybe it's all a front. Maybe that if you just walked across several blocks, you could find one prioritized to harbor, not deter. Maybe you'll find a suburb, where you can comfortably lay down on the flat grass. But in the meantime, you are still subject to what should be a bustling city center, built to welcome people from all walks of life, yet distorted to dissuade.

{{User:Liminalityyyyy/Template:ClassicImageBox|file=Gottabequick.jpg|text= |width=440px}}

While strolling the city streets, it starts to drizzle. It is a negligible annoyance at first, yet it slowly builds up over time. After five minutes you start hearing the rain all over, the sounds of droplets over metal roofs, even the roar of lightning at one point. Your body's impulse to seek shelter activates. But there is none. There are awnings all over, and shadows to seek shelter from the storm, but they are all 'decorated' with rocks and bollards, whose prohibitive nature is ironically enough, clear as day. The best you are getting is another bus stop, with a thin canopy and a metal, wavy bench. The silver lining is that you aren't going to sleep on it, but its inhuman design renders it uncanny.

You can never find true respite, as the rain slanting towards your direction, combined with the ropey glass canopy, renders your calves and feet soaked in rain. Wet boots and pants that will take ages to dry. And there is no space underneath the bench for you to tuck your feet in. The design of the bench warps it to where it's slightly slanted towards the rain, so if you lay on the bench, you will fall to the ground, where the downpour insults your fall. Keeping your feet on the ground to weather the storm is the sensible compromise.

But that is the thing. A compromise. Everything is fractured in this place. First it was the [[Level 11|lifeless and endless constructs]], to the inviting yet barring city center. What's next after this?

This place was not meant for humans to inhabit. It is a prison, for which the [[The Narrator|warden]] remains myth and legend.

Even if you somehow make it back home, reintegrating into society is challenging. You're doomed to always make a compromise. 

There is nothing you can do. Maybe the rain will stop soon enough. Or maybe you can barrel through it to find an exit. But where will you end up? It's a gamble at best.

So your best bet now is to... ''wait...''
